\sqrt{|e^{-y}\cos x + ie^{-y}\sin x|} = e^{-y}
1
e^{-y}
{e^{ix}} = \cos (x) + i\sin (x)
\left| {{e^{ix}}} \right| = \sqrt {{{\cos }^2}(x) + {{\sin }^2}(x)} = 1
z = x + iy
|z| = \sqrt{x^2+y^2}
z = e^{-y} \cos x + i e^{-y}\sin x
\Re (z) = e^{-y} \cos x
\Im (z) = e^{-y}\sin x
y \in \mathbb R
|z| = \sqrt{(e^{-y} \cos x)^2 + (e^{-y}\sin x)^2} = \sqrt{e^{-2y} ((\cos x)^2 + (\sin x)^2)} = \sqrt{e^{-2y}} = e^{-y}
